_arr v3.0 ( Apr 2022 by digi_cs )
_______________________________________________________
_____
OVERVIEW
library _arr (array.inc) contains function set (28) for basic working with
an arrays
the advantages of this library are overpowered below:
- high performance
join: advanced AIR2-core
for details see AIR
- maximum join string length: up to 900MB
- flexible parameter's interface:
- direct/omit/relative parameter's form
- supporting two types of arrays
- allows user to create it's own new array functions(2)
- reduced library source size
- requiring limitation is: 100 - 128 KB (this release: 75KB)
- well tested
- self3mod
- self modification feature:
- allows user to create it's own new array functions(2)
see PERFORMANCE for details

ARRAY JOINING
B[ 0 ] = "b0"
A[ 1 ] = "a1" ; B[ 1 ] = "b1"
A[ 2 ] = "a2" ; B[ 2 ] = "b2"
A[ 3 ] = "a3" ; B[ 3 ] = "b3"
_reta( A ) == "a1a2a3" # A[1] A[2] A[3]
_retad( A, -1 ) == "a3a2a1" # A[3] A[2] A[1]
_retas( A, "-" ) == "a1-a2-a3" # A[1] "-" A[2] "-" A[3]
_retab( A, B ) == "b0a1b1a2b2a3b3" # B[0] A[1] B[1] A[2] B[2]
A[3] B[3]
_retabs( A, B, "-" ) == "a1b1-a2b2-a3b3" # A[1] B[1] "-" A[2] B[2] "-"
A[3] B[3]
- joining elements of an array:
split( "abc", A, "" )
_reta( A ) == "abc"
- joining elements of an array in reversed order:
split( "abc", A, "" )
_retad( A, -1 ) == "cba"
- joining elements of an array using separator:
split( "abc", A, "" )
_retas( A, "-" ) == "a-b-c"
- joining elements of the two arrays:
patsplit( t, A, /regexp/, B )
_retab( A, B ) == t
- typical patsplit, processing loop and join back:
t == source string
if ( patsplit( t, T, /regexp/, D ) ) {
for ( t = 1; t in T; t++ )
T[ t ] = ... processing T[ t ]
t = _retab( T, D ) }
t == processed source string
- genearte an data by pieces and gets the result:
"" in D
while ...
...D[ length( D ) ] = ... peace of result
d = _reta( D )
ARRAY DEFINITIONS
- providing an undefined arrays A[ "A" ] and A[ "B" ]:
# delete A
patsplit( ..., A[ _defa( "A", A ) ], ..., A[ _defa( "B", A ) ] )
- deleting an element of an array from the gawk expression mode:
expression ... _delete( "PROCINFO", SYMTAB ) ... expression
- clearing global ARRAY through the SYMTAB:
_dela( SYMTAB[ "ARRAY" ] )
due to SYMTAB delete protection user isn't able to performing:
delete SYMTAB[ "ARRAY" ]
even if it's could be possible the _dela() isn't deletes
specified index but just clearing it while delete statement will
remove index from an array
DATA MOVEMENTS
- copy array to array:
_movaa( D, S )
- get the name of an array:
_nama( PROCINFO ) == "PROCINFO"
- dumping an array:
split( "a0b1c", A, /[0-9]/, B )
print _dumpa( A )
outputs:
- dumping two arrays:
split( "a0b1c", A, /[0-9]/, B )
print _dumpab( A, B )
outputs:

FUNCSET
library contains five very important functions for array joining making awk
programming much easier and effective. the programming design is using an
elements of linear programming solutions with the primal priority to fastly
operates with a large amount of indexes and the big data sizes.
please note that all parameters for a functions implemented below have the
same common parameter determination system allowing to omit or providing its in
a relative form. see PARAMETERs DETERMINATION for details.
the programming environment include special definition called as hids:
BEGIN_
END_
NAMA_
NAMASTRICT_
hid is the global variable with an unique strong value assigned. the
typical usage of hids is as special indexes in an arrays or as
the special values meaning something more than just a value. see HIDs
for details
please note that the parameter's names in the followed description of library
functions have some special rules:
- low case parameter's name means that parameter's type is not untyped
or array
- case-up parameter's name means an array parameter
- mixed-case parameter's name means that parameter may be an array
or any other except untyped
_reta( A, a, q, x, Sep, b, y )
_retas( A, Sep, a, q, x, b, y )
_retad( A, x, a, q, Sep, b, y )
A - source array A
a - start index a
q - number of elements to join
x - index step a
Sep - separator
source array B:
b - start index b
y - index step b
joins `q of an elements of an array `A with numeric indexes starting
from `a with using index step `x and with the separator `Sep:
note: all three functions do the same job and differs from each other
only by parameter's order.
note: if `Sep is an array then function call will be redirected to
_retab() function like follows:
return _retab( A, Sep, a, q, b, x, y )
example 1:
join 3 elements starting from index 2 without an separator and
using index step +1:
_reta( A, 2, 3, 1 )
_retad( A, 1, 2, 3 )
_retas( A, "", 2, 3, 1 )
will cause to return like:
return A[2] A[3] A[4]
example 2:
join 3 elements starting from index 2 without an separator and
using index step -1 (reversed order):
_retad( A, -1, 2, 3 )
_reta( A, 2, 3, -1 )
_retas( A, "", 2, 3, -1 )
will cause to return like:
return A[2] A[1] A[0]
example 3:
join 3 elements starting from index 2 with separator "-" and
using index step -1:
_retas( A, "-", 2, 3, -1 )
_reta( A, 2, 3, -1, "-" )
_retad( A, -1, 2, 3, "-" )
will cause to return like:
return A[2] "-" A[1] "-" A[0]
_retab( A, B, a, q, b, x, y, Sep )
_retabs( A, B, Sep, a, q, b, x, y )
A - source array A
B - source array B
a - start index a
q - number of elements to join
b - start index b
x - index step a
y - index step b
Sep - separator
joins `q of element-pairs of an arrays `A and `B with numeric indexes
starting from `a/`b and using index step in `x/`y for array `A/`B
appropriately and with the separator `Sep:
note: both functions do the same job and differs from each other only
by parameter's order
note: _retab(): if `Sep isn't equals to empty string ( != "" ) then
functon call will be redirected to _retabs( A, B, Sep, a, q, b, x, y
)
note: _retabs(): if `Sep equals to empty string ( != "" ) then functon
call will be redirected to _retab( A, B, a, q, b, x, y )
example 1:
_retab( A, B, 1, 3, 5, 1, -1 )
will cause to return like:
return A[1] B[5] A[2] B[4] A[3] B[3]
example 2:
_retabs( A, B, "-", 1, 3, 5, 1, -1 )
will cause to return like:
return A[1] B[5] "-" A[2] B[4] "-" A[3] B[3]
_retab() was designed as the opposite of the built-ins split() and
patsplit() functions that are called with the four parameters.
here is the typical usage example:
example:
# typical patsplit, processing loop and joinback
if ( patsplit( t, T, /.../, D ) ) {
for ( t = 1; t in T; t++ )
T[ t ] = ... T[ t ] ... # processing
t = _retab( T, D ) }
...
_defa( i, A )
defines `A[ `i ] as an clear array.
if `A[ `i ] is already defined as an array then _defa() always clear
it.
returns `i.
example:
patsplit( ..., T[ _defa( "A", T ) ], ..., T[ _defa( "B", T )
]
_leta( i, A )
defines `A[ `i ] as an array.
if `A[ `i ] is already defined as an array then nothing is doing.
returns `i.
example:
-
_dela( A, v )
clear array `A from inside.
there is difference between using statement:
delete `A[ `i ]
and a function call:
_dela( `A[ `i ] )
the last one do not deleting index `i from array `A while delete
statement will remove index `i from array `A.
this may be useful in case if for example array `A is the SYMTAB array
that is stricted for elements deleting.
returns `v.
example:
-
_delete( i, A )
delete index `i from array `A.
allows user to perform deleteing index from an array without using
statement.
also in gawk version before 5.x this function allows to bypass
deleting index protection from arrays SYMTAB/FUNCTAB. for gawk 5.x it
is no longer actual cause now SYMTAB have dynamic protection.
returns `i.
example:
-
_iav( i, A, Val )
if index `i is exist in `A then returns `A[ `i ]
otherwise returns `Val
if returned value `A[ `i ] or `Val is an array then returns
_reta( `A[ `i ] / `Val )
example:
-
_iavd( i, A, Val )
same as _iav() but in case if `i in `A then post-deleting `A[ `i ]
will be performed
example:
-
_movaa( D, S )
copies all indexes of array `S to array `D.
destination indexes will be always deleted if its exist in `D.
returns null (unassigned).
example:
-
_moviav( i, A, Val )
writes `Val to `A[ `i ].
if `Val is untyped then `A[ `i ] will be deleted.
if `Val and `A[ `i ] are both an arrays then `A[ `i ] will be deleted
first and then recreated.
returns `i.
example:
-
_movaia( D, i, S )
copies state of `S[ `i ] to `D[ `i ].
if `i is not exist in `S then `D[ `i ] will be deleted.
if `S[ `i ] and `D[ `i ] are both an arrays then `D[ `i ] will be deleted
first and then recreated.
returns `i.
example:
-
_moviaia( di, D, si, S )
copies state of `S[ `si ] to `D[ `di ].
if `si is not exist in `S then `D[ `di ] will be deleted.
if `S[ `si ] and `D[ `di ] are both an arrays then `D[ `di ] will be
deleted first and then recreated.
returns `di.
example:
-
_sama( A, B )
function returns true (1) in case if a given arrays `A and `B are
the same array.
example:
-
_nama( T, P, prefix, X, mode )
`T - target array
`P - parent array
`prefix - prefix string
`X - exclude array
`mode - nested-flag (if true then nested array seeking enable)
low effective. primarily it's intresting in debug reasons.
_nama() is exotic function that's returns the symbolic name of the
given target array `T - in case if it's global or nested of the
global. the returned symbolic name is relative from the
given array `P - that its if omitted then SYMTAB will be used.
optional array `X may implement exclusions for the name determination
process: the indexes thats present in `X will not been available
for name determination process.
the returned symbolic name - if it's detected - will be prefixed by
the `prefix.
the `mode - if true - enables recursive scan of the nested arrays.
if `mode is equals to 0 then nested arrays scaning will be disabled.
if `mode is omitted ( =="" ) then state of globvar _NAMA_NESTEDARR
will be used.
example:
print _nama( PROCINFO )
outputs:
PROCINFO
example 2:
HOTEL[ "" ]
abc( HOTEL )
func abc( A ) {
print _nama( A ) "'" }
outputs:
HOTEL'

optional array `X may contains indexes that are will be skipped while
dump is generated and will not a part of its.
_dumpa() groups indexes in to the four categories and generating dump
of an array in the following order:
- hid indexes ( see HIDs )
- string indexes (all that is not hid, numeric or pointer)
- numeric indexes
- pointer's indexes ( index in _CLASSPTR )
BEGIN_/END_ arrays have special form in a dump at numeric indexes part:
- the index that is pointed by BEGIN_ (in example below: 6 )
is having double extra spaces inserted before the index
field
- the index that is pointed by the END_ (in example below: 1)
is having single extra space inserted before index field
- an indexes that are located between BEGIN_ and END_ haves
triple extra spaces inserted before index field
example:
[ -1 ] = -1
[ 0 ] = 0
[ 1 ] = 1 <- BEGIN_
[ 3 ] = 3
[ 4 ] = 4
[ 5 ] = 5
[ 6 ] = 6 <- END_
[ 7 ] = 7
_dumpa() output form is controlled by the following global var set:
_DUMPA_DATA_MAXMULTILN
default: 5
maximum data height
_DUMPA_INDEX_MAXMULTILN
default: 5
maximum index height
_DUMPA_DUMPCHR
default: @/[\x00-\x08\x0B\x0C\x0E-\x1F\x7F-\xFF]/
contains regexp
if data string is match with this regexp then data string
will be hex-dumped instead of text form
_DUMPA_DUMPWIDTH
default: 16
width of string dump (in bytes)
_DUMPA_DUMPASC
default: 1 (enabled)
if true then hex-dump will include asc-characters column
_DUMPA_DUMPASCDOTCHR
default: @/[\x00-\x1F\x7F]/
contains regexp
characters that are matchs with this regexp will be
replaced in asc-characters column by the "."-dot
character
_DUMPA_MAXINDEX
default: -1
not implemented
contains number of indexes that if exceeds will leads to
dump index reducing
note: if equals to -1 then disabled
_DUMPA_STARTLENSPEC
default: 0 (disabled)
if true then enables special form of the elements output
with indexes like:
1, "start"
1, "length"
note that special form is requiring appropriate numeric
index existance in an array. in case of above the numeric
index 1 is required to be exist in an array

PARAMETERs DETERMINATION
all array-joining functions use a common parameter determination system
located in the _reta_startlen() function. the operation of this function is
described below.
if user wants to creates an it's own special array functions then are may
use _reta_startlen() function to pre-determinate a parameters.
the following is the detailed explanation of the how _reta_startlen() works.
see also ARRAY TYPES
the parameters determination process starts by getting information about
a given array(s) and storing its in the special set of the global vars:
_reta_tp - type: array type ( C/B )
C - COMMON type array
B - BEGIN/END type array
see ARRAY TYPES
_reta_first - first: index of the first index in a given array
_reta_last - last: index of the last index in a given array
_reta_ax - arrstep: array index step
the arrstep - array index step - may be determinated by `AB[ STEP_ ] if it's
exist in a given array:
- if STEP_ is exist in a given array then it's contains exact array
index step:
arrstep = `AB[ STEP_ ]
- otherwise arrstep is equals to 1*
* there is some exception described in ARRAY TYPES
do not confuse the arrstep and the index step parameter provided when
calling an array-join functions.
although if when calling such a function the index step parameter is
omitted ( == "" ) then its will be equals to the array index
step.
the arrstep is actually index step that is using while write-to-array
operations performed.
the idxstep - index step parameter that's will be consider further
- provided to an array joining functions is using it's while
read-from-array operations performed.
see below for a details
the first index of an array is may contained at `AB[ BEGIN_ ] if it's exist
in an array:
- if BEGIN_ is exist in a given array then its contains first array's
index:
first = `AB[ BEGIN_ ]
- otherwise first index of an array will be calculated as the follows:
first = ! ( 0 in `AB )
that is: the first index in a given array will be 0 if the index 0
is existed in a given array. otherwise it's will be equal to
1
the last index of an array may be determinated by `AB[ END_ ] if it's existed
in an array that is the pointer beyond the last element of an array
( == last + arrstep ):
- if END_ is exist in a given array then last index of a given array
will be calculated as follows:
last = `AB[ END_ ] - arrstep
- otherwise last index of an array will be calculated as the follows:
last = first + ( _reta_length( `AB ) - 1 ) * arrstep
note: that _reta_length returns number of indexes in a given
array regardless of the presence or absence of the following
indexes inside it:
BEGIN_
END_
STEP_
`x/`y - idxstep: index step parameter for array `A/`B
next,the parameter determination system needs to know the `idxstep - index
step parameter while using it as the current index pointer modifier while joining
an elements
note that index step value is determinated by the _reta_start() function
that is placing the results in the globvar _reta_x
array v3 supports index step parameter that is adding to `a/`b after each
read- from-array operation is performed:
... A[a]B[b] A[a+=x]B[b+=y] ...
`xy may be any number including negatives that allows to join array's
elements in forward or reversed order
if `xy is omitted ( == "" ) then it's will be equals to default index step.
the default index step is always equals to 1 except in case if STEP_ is exist
in a given array. if thus then default index step will be loaded from `AB[ STEP_
].
note: that there is another exception when default index step may be equals
to -1. see ARRAY TYPES for details.
if `xy is present ( != "" ) then its will be converted to a number:
_reta_x = 0 + `xy
`a/`b - start index parameter for array `A/`B
then parameters determination system is calculating the start index of the
join process.
`ab determinates start index of the join process.
note that start index value is determinated by the _reta_start() function
that is placing the results in the globvar _reta_a
`ab may be omitted ( == "" ) and then it's will be targeted at the first
or last (depending from a given index step polarity) index of a given array:
- if index step polarity is positive ( >= 0 ) then `ab will be equals
to the first array index (_reta_first)
- if index step polarity is negative ( < 0 ) then `ab will be equals
to the last array index (_reta_last)
`ab can also contain the leading character "^" or "$" followed by an optional
decimal number. in this case, it's the relative form of the start index.
it is calculated by skipping the specified number of indexes counted from
the first or last (depending on index step polarity) index of a given array:
example 1:
A[ 0 ] = a # $3 or ^0
A[ 1 ] = b # $2 or ^1
A[ 2 ] = c # $1 or ^2
A[ 3 ] = d # $0 or ^3
_reta( A, "$2" ) == "bcd"
_retad( A, -1, "^1" ) == "ba"
example 2:
A[ BEGIN_ ] = -2
A[ -2 ] = a # $5 or ^0
A[ -1 ] = b # $4 or ^1
A[ 0 ] = c # $3 or ^2
A[ 1 ] = d # $2 or ^3
A[ 2 ] = e # $1 or ^4
A[ 3 ] = f # $0 or ^5
A[ END_ ] = 4
_retad( A, -1, "^2" ) == "cba"
in other cases `ab is always interpreted as the exact start index of the
join- process:
_reta( A, 4 )
_reta( A, -3 )
_reta( A, 3.14159 )
_reta( A, 0 )
_reta( A, "+1" )
`q - quantity: numer of elements to return (index range)
finally parameters determination system calculates the number of elements
to join while joining process.
`q may be present as an exact positive value (number or strnum)
in this case number of returned elements will be equals to integer
of
`q:
number = int( `q )
`q may be present as an negative value
in this case its will be interpreted as: ... "return elements starting
from determinated start index and until to last/first (depending on index
step polarity) element of a given array `A.
example:
A[ 0 ]= a
A[ 1 ]= b
A[ 2 ]= c
A[ 3 ]= d
_reta( A, 1, -1 ) == "bc"
_reta( A, 2, -1, -1 ) == "cb"
`q may be omitted ( == "" ) in this case it's will be autodetected and will
cover array's indexes starting from determinated start index and until the
last/first (depending on index step polarity) index of a given array:
if index step polarity is positive ( >= 0 ) then `q will be calculated
for covering all elements starting from determinated start index until
the last element of an array:
example:
A[ 0 ]= a
A[ 1 ]= b
A[ 2 ]= c
A[ 3 ]= d
_reta( A, 1, "", 1 ) == "bcd"
if index step polarity is negative ( < 0 ) then `q will be calculated
for covering all elements starting from determinated start index until
the first element of an array:
example:
A[ 0 ]= a
A[ 1 ]= b
A[ 2 ]= c
A[ 3 ]= d
_reta( A, 2, "", -1 ) == "cba"

ARRAY TYPES
COMMON array
an common array is the typical post- split/patsplit array:
- common array indexes is starting from index 0 or 1
- all numeric indexes is present sequentially
- there is no other indexes in an array except sequential numeric
this is except index STEP_ that's may be present in a
common array
- the array index step is equals to: +1
BEGIN/END(BE) array
BE array is determinated by existance in an array index BEGIN_ or/and
END_
- A[ BEGIN_ ] contains the first index in an array
- A[ END_ ] contains the beyond the last index of an array
example:
A[ BEGIN_ ] = -2
A[ -2 ] = "a"
A[ -1 ] = "b"
A[ 0 ] = "c"
A[ 1 ] = "d"
A[ 2 ] = "e"
A[ 3 ] = "f"
A[ END_ ] = 4
_reta( A ) == "abcdef"
if A[ BEGIN_ ] == A[ END_ ] then BE-array is empty
- A[ STEP_ ] contains the array index step that's may be positive
or negative:
example:
A[ END_ ] = -3
A[ -2 ] = "f"
A[ -1 ] = "e"
A[ 0 ] = "d"
A[ 1 ] = "c"
A[ 2 ] = "b"
A[ 3 ] = "a"
A[ BEGIN_ ] = 3
A[ STEP_ ] = -1
_reta( A ) == "abcdef"
note that if STEP_ is not exist in an array then array
index step will be equals to: +1. this is except note2
note2: if STEP_ is not exist in an array AND both BEGIN_
and END_ are exist in an array AND BEGIN_ is more than END_
then array index step will be equals to: -1
example:
A[ END_ ] = -3
A[ -2 ] = "f"
A[ -1 ] = "e"
A[ 0 ] = "d"
A[ 1 ] = "c"
A[ 2 ] = "b"
A[ 3 ] = "a"
A[ BEGIN_ ] = 3
_reta( A ) == "abcdef"
- BE array may contains any number of the any indexes

SELF3MOD
the library have self-modification feature allowing for user to rebuild
library source file using other constant values.
the constant values are placed in the gawk commentaries. depending from it's
values the library file source will be self-modificated.
this feature is disabled by default but user may activate it by uncommenting
_self3mod() function call at the BEGIN area of the library source file.
user also must provide filepath to the library source file as the parameter
for _self3mod()
user may easily implementing the simple repeatatives in the source file using
_self3mod feature
_self3mod commands are placed in the gawk commentaries with preceeding
double space characters:
... # x63
... # *63
if such combination is found in an source line then it's processed as follows:
whole source line is splited by the separator that is the double space
characters
each part is the self3mod command's parameter 1, 2 and so on
the last part is the self3mod itself
note that parameters 3+ is always skipped
then if last part is equals to:
' xNumber' - then this is the single line repeater
command
or
' *Number' - then this is the multi line repeater
command
otherwise command will be skipped and source line pass to the result
without changes
single line repeater
pass parameter1 " " parameter2 " " ( duplicates parameter2 " " )
command
note that parameter 1 is passed with replacement decimal numbers by
detailed description of self3mod commands is currently unfinished.

HIDs
hids is the special definition. each hid is the global variable that's have
assigned by the special unique value. this unique value may be found as the
index in the global array _HID.
traditionally hids have upper cased name with the single uderscore character
at the end:
the hid's usage motivation is simple:
example:
let's for example you want defines in an array - the subarray that will
contain some list-type information (just for example). but if
you're naming index of the subarray someway like "LIST" - it's will be
good chance that such index will be conflicted with the other possible
indexes of the original array. hid - is the solution for this
we're should define in such case hid named like LIST_. this mean that
the global var LIST_ will be defined and special unique value should to
be assigned to it
now we can define subarray using content of globvar LIST_ as the index
of an subaray:
A[ LIST_ ]
please note that hids is the part of special environment that this library
is not includes. because of public version this library should operate
without requiring any external resources.
